<div id="Idea_2975"><div id="IdeaScale_IdeaTitle">
<a href="/akira/dtd/2975-4049"><span id="IdeaTitle_2975">Mandate XBRL Filings at the SEC&nbsp;</span></a>
</div>
<table width=@%">  <tr>    <td valign="top"><div id="IdeaScale_IdeaSubTitle"><b><a href="http://opengov.ideascale.com/akira/pmd/4301-4049">mark</a></b> <span class="IdeaScale_SecondaryText">8 days ago</span></div></td>    <td align="right" valign="top"></td>  </tr></table>
<div id="IdeaScale_IdeaContent">Today the SEC operates a voluntary program for companies to file their SEC documents in XML especially designed for business reporting called XBRL.  Most companies to not use this program.   For most companies, the data is filed in text and html that make it very time consuming to convert into a spreadsheet suitable for analyzing the financial information.   If this data was avaiable in the XML dialect represented by XBRL, it would take much less time for an investor to create a financial analysis.<br/><br/></div>
<div id="IdeaScale_IdeaFooter"><span style="border-right: 1px solid silver; margin:0 10px 0 0; padding: 0 5px 0 0; color: #666;"><a id="DiscussionTopic_2975" href="javascript:ajaxLink('DiscussionTopicComment_2975', '/akira/discussion.do?mode=comment&dbid=2236&topicID=2975')">Comments (2)</a></span><span id="DiscussionTopicTag_2975"><a href="/akira/ideafactory.do?discussionID=2236">Making Data More Accessible</a>,&nbsp;<a href="/akira/ideafactory.do?mode=tag&tag=sec xbrl investors finance">sec xbrl investors finance</a></span></div><div style="margin-top:3px;" id="DiscussionTopicComment_2975"></div>
